# Clean Architecture Dependency Rule

```
Api ──► Application ──► Domain
 │           │
 └──► Infrastructure ──► Application (interfaces) ──► Domain
```

## Hard rules (non-negotiable)

- **Domain** has ZERO references to other projects. NO `Microsoft.*`, NO `EntityFrameworkCore`, NO `AspNetCore`.
- **Application** references **Domain only**. Defines interfaces in `Application/Common/Interfaces/`; Infrastructure implements them.
- **Infrastructure** references Application + Domain. ALL framework-specific code (EF, S3, FCM, MassTransit, NodaTime adapters) lives here.
- **Api** references Application + Infrastructure (for DI composition). Keep controllers thin — delegate to `ISender.Send(command)`.

## Vertical slice in Application

Each use case is one folder with up to 4 files:

```
Application/Features/<Module>/<UseCase>/
├── <Name>Command.cs            // record ... : IRequest<Result<T>>
├── <Name>CommandHandler.cs     // sealed class with BR XML doc
├── <Name>CommandValidator.cs   // FluentValidation
└── <Name>Response.cs           // optional, only when shape is custom
```

## Forbidden patterns

```csharp
// ❌ BAD — EF leak in Application
using Microsoft.EntityFrameworkCore;        // Only IApplicationDbContext is allowed.

// ❌ BAD — IHttpContextAccessor in Application
public class Handler(IHttpContextAccessor http) { ... }

// ✅ GOOD — abstract via ICurrentUser, implement in Infrastructure
public class Handler(ICurrentUser user) { ... }
```

If you see any forbidden pattern, **stop and fix** before continuing.
